Basic Git Commands:
	
1. git config
		
		Set or See the Configuration of the git.

2. git config --global user.name [Firstname_Lastname]
		
		This command will set the name. To configure your user name to be used by Git.

3. git config --global user.email [email_address]
		
		To configure your email to be used by Git, 

4. git init
		
		Type the following at the prompt to initialize the folder as a Git repository.

5. git status
		
		Checking your Git repository status. Checks the current status of the folder.

6. git add [filename] or git add .

		Add files to the staging area of your Git repository. The .(dot) will add all files in the directory will be added.

7. git commit -m "Message"
		
		Commit the current staging area to your Git repository. Commit the changes to the git repository.

8. git remote add origin [repo.URL]
		
		Set up your local repository to link to your online Git repository.Add the remote online repository.

9. git push origin master
		
		Push the commits to the online repository. Push the local git repository to the origin to the master branch.

10. git clone [repo.URL]

		Clone an online git reposritory to your computer.

11. date
		display the date and time

12. cal
		display the calendar of the current month.

	cal -m Feb 1998

		It will display the Febravary month of 1998 year.

13. pwd 
		
		To print the working directory.

14. cd 

		It is change the directory.

15. cd ~
		
		It will directly go to the home directory.

16. ls 

		The ls command list all files in the directory.

17. ls -l 

		The ls -l command will display the detailed info in colums.

18. ls -R
		
		Recursively display the subdirectories.

19. ls -S
		
		Sort by size.

20. less [filename]
	
		Shows the contents inside the file.

21. mkdir [directory_name]

		It will create a directory with specified name.

22. mkdir [dir1] [dir2] [dir3]

		We can also create multiple directories using the above command.

23. cp file1 file2

		Copy the single file to file2

24. cp file1 file2 dir1

		Copy the file1 and file2 into directory.

25. cp -r dir1 dir2
		
		Copy the contents of dir1 to dir2.

26. mv file1 file2

		The mv command is to rename the particular file . Otherwise it will move to another dir.

27. rm <item>

		It will remove the item.

28. rm -r <item>
		
		It will remove the contents of the item.

29. rm -r dir1 dir2

		Delete the both the file and the contents.

30. wget [location]

		The wget command is to command line program for the file downloading.

31. unzip [file_name]

		It will unzip the file.

32. head file.txt

		It will displays the top 10 in the file. It is a default option.

33. head -n 100 file.txt

		It will display the top 100 in the file.

34. tail file.txt

		It will display bottom 10 of the file.

35. tail -n 5 file.txt

		It will diplay the bottom 5 of the file.

36. wc file.txt
		
		It will display the number of lines, words, bytes contained in the files.

37. wc -l 

		It will display the number of lines in the file.

38. wc -w 

		Display the number of words

39. wc - m 

		Display the number of character.

40. grep [search_word] file.txt

		Display the serach_word in the file.txt

41. grep [search_word] file_*

		Display the search word using wildcards .

42. cat file.txt
		
		Display the content in the file same as the less command.

43. sort file.txt

		Sort the file in the ascending order.

44. sort file.txt > sort1.txt

		It will sort the file and save it in an another file.

45. sort - r file.txt
	
		Display in the reverse order.

   